{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f0529250-a3ce-408f-b264-290129f30ae5","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening and what to fix:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **test ID generation algorithm**. Azure DevOps tracks history by test ID, so every test looks new. To restore the legacy IDs, add this to your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr keep the new IDs and accept a one-time history reset (the new scheme is more deterministic).\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — no test is running yet, so `TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it returned the name of whichever test happened to trigger class init first (non-deterministic and misleading).\n\n**Fix your code** — remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit`:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead, or\n    // move per-test logic to [TestInitialize]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other key v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`[TestMethod]` + `[DataRow]`** | `[DataTestMethod]` is no longer needed; `[TestMethod]` now works with `[DataRow]` directly |\n| **MSTest runner** | The `MSTest` meta-package defaults to the new **MSTest runner** instead of VSTest — behavior around parallelism and output may differ |\n| **Parallel execution** | Defaults may differ; review `[Parallelize]` and runsettings |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` (floats)** | Delta comparison semantics tightened — verify any floating-point assertions |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | May be read-only in some lifecycle phases |\n| **Timeout behavior** | `[Timeout]` now uses `CancellationToken` cooperative cancellation by default instead of thread-abort |\n\nWould you like me to patch your `SetupTests.cs` to fix the `ClassInitialize` issue?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"da9acaf3-8983-4f9f-8fdc-947acaa80efb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has two specific issues and is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me address both issues and provide broader guidance.\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps**: In MSTest v4, the default **test ID generation strategy** changed. MSTest v3 used a legacy ID scheme, and v4 switched to a new deterministic ID algorithm. Since Azure DevOps tracks test history by test ID, the new IDs make every test look like a brand new test. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` in the project file or runsettings.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a *class-level* context, not associated with any specific test. Accessing `TestName` on it throws an `InvalidOperationException` because there is no test running yet at class-initialization time. \n\nThe v4 behavior is intentional—v3 would non-deterministically return whichever test happened to trigger the class initialization first. Beyond these two issues, there are a few other changes worth noting: `[TestMethod]` now accepts `[DataRow]` attributes directly since v4 unified the test method types, floating-point assertion deltas may behave differently, and `TestContext.Properties` is read-only in certain scenarios.\n\nI should also mention deployment item handling, parallel execution defaults, and the shift toward the new MSTest runner over VSTest when using the meta-package. Let me put together a comprehensive response that addresses their specific problems and covers these broader compatibility concerns.","outputTokens":1039,"requestId":"0847:44A9F:835275C:925D2D7:69EAD71D"},"id":"bef866f7-46fa-4403-9d77-4f45a72dcb16","timestamp":"2026-04-24T02:36:36.466Z","parentId":"9f4c4412-d2ff-4952-971d-02e9b4de9588"}
